Adjust rack to middle position (middle and top positions for 4 servings) and preheat #oven{} to 450 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Dice @potatoes{12%ounce} into ½-inch pieces. Roughly chop @parsley{¼%ounce}.

Trim and discard bottom 1 inch from @asparagus{6%ounce}.

Place @garlic cloves{2} in the center of a small piece of #foil{}; drizzle with @cooking oil{1%tablespoon} and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Cinch into a packet and place on a #baking sheet{}. Roast on middle rack for ~{10%minutes} (you'll add more to the sheet then).

Meanwhile, place potatoes in a #medium pot{} with enough salted water to cover by 2 inches. Bring to a boil and cook until tender, ~{15-20%minutes}. Reserve ½ cup potato cooking liquid (¾ cup for 4 servings), then drain. Return potatoes to pot and cover to keep warm.

While potatoes cook, combine @panko breadcrumbs{¼%cup}, parsley, half the @parmesan cheese{3%tablespoon} (you'll use the rest later), @olive oil{1%tablespoon}, and a pinch of salt and pepper in a #medium bowl{}.

Pat @salmon{10%ounce} dry with #paper towels{} and season all over with salt and pepper. Place on a #plate{}; drizzle skin sides with @olive oil{}; rub to coat. Place, skin sides down, on plate.

Evenly spread tops with a thin layer of half a packet of @dijon mustard{4%teaspoon} (whole packet for 4 servings). Mound tops with panko mixture, pressing firmly to adhere.

Once garlic has roasted ~{10%minutes}, remove sheet from oven. Carefully add salmon to one side of sheet. Toss asparagus on empty side with a drizzle of oil, salt, and pepper.

Return to middle rack and roast until asparagus and garlic are tender, and salmon is golden brown and cooked through, ~{10-12%minutes}. (For 4 servings, toss asparagus on a second baking sheet; roast asparagus on middle rack and salmon on top rack.)

To pot with potatoes, add @sour cream{3%tablespoon}, roasted garlic with its oil, half the @cream sauce base{4%ounce}, remaining parmesan, and @butter{2%tablespoon}. Mash with a #potato masher{} or fork until smooth and creamy, adding splashes of reserved potato cooking liquid as needed. Taste and season with salt and pepper.

Heat a #small pan{} over medium-high heat. Add half the @white wine vinegar{5%teaspoon} (save the rest for another use), remaining cream sauce base, remaining mustard, and @sugar{1%teaspoon}. Cook, stirring occasionally, until sauce begins to thicken, ~{2-4%minutes}. Remove from heat and stir in @butter{1%tablespoon}.

Taste and season with salt and pepper.

Divide salmon, asparagus, and mashed potatoes between #plates{}. Drizzle salmon with creamy mustard sauce and serve.

> Salmon is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.